description.value: Head of terracotta horse with incised detail.  The head of a bridled and harnessed horse, broken from a figure modelled in the round. The eyes are prominent, the nostrils flare, and the upper teeth and the tongue are shown. Some elements of the bridle are decorated with close cross-hatching, as is the right eyebrow and the front of the mane, part of which is broken away.  From a two-piece mould, with considerable hand-tooling; much of the harness has been added after the object left the mould; body hollow, head probably solid.   Micaceous orange-brown Nile silt; very slight traces of a white dressing.

description.value: Head of Tyche with mural crown.  A female head broken from a figure, wearing a mural crown: a city Tyche or possibly Cybele. Her hair is parted in the centre and falls in locks beside her face. The crown surmounting her hair is tall and has almost vertical walls; it is open at the top. Drapery hangs from the crown, surviving only on the left side of the head. She may wear a choker-like necklace.   Hollow; two-piece mould. Micaceous orange-brown Nile silt with a red and grey-brown core. Traces remain of a white dressing applied to the front; the hair is painted red and blue paint survives on the crown.

description.value: Egyptian terracotta figure of Isis-Nike riding a horse. Isis-Nike on horseback, the horse galloping to right, its rear end lost. Isis, who is over-large for the horse, sits side saddle and wears a long chiton, and a himation that falls over both shoulders. Her hair is parted in the centre and falls in front of her shoulders in Isis-locks. She has a large and complex headdress of a tightly woven and bound wreath, with floral-bunches and leaves, across which a horizontal garland is bound: a wide binding-lappet blows back on her right shoulder; above all is a crown of horns, disc and feathers. A triangular harp is held to her left shoulder, and her raised right-hand holds a palm branch, the top of which is broken away. The horse, whose left foreleg is injured, rides down a man, only the head and a hand of whom is preserved. At first sight he looks very Bes-like, but he is a grotesque processional figure, wearing a festive wreath bound with a horizontal garland, and puffing out his cheeks to play double pipes, his left hand gripping one of the pipes. The back is plain, with a circular vent.   Hollow, from two-piece mould, with traces of a white dressing on the front, now stained a drab colour. This coating overlies the horse in places, which had previously been painted a deep pink, colour. Minute traces of pink survive on top of the coating on the palm branch, on the wreath just above her right shoulder and. on her chiton below her right arm; a few flecks of green paint can be seen in places. Red-brown Nile silt, with abundant fine gold mica, quartz and white inclusions.

description.value:
Fragmentary quartzite-sandstone head of a male figure.

He has a broad shaven head, with subtle modelling of the cranium. His ears project slightly forwards,and have been carefully rendered. His brow is deep set and his eyes are almond shaped with a heavy upper eyelid. There is a subtle suggestion of the thinner skin underneath the eyes. His nose is long and broad at the nostrils, with a slight cupid's bow visible above the upper lip. His lower lip, which is larger than his upper lip, slopes down at the centre and is sharply incised along the edge. The outer corners of his mouth are slightly upturned, suggesting a small smile. His cheekbones and jawline are particularly prominent, with a further ridge of flesh visible on either side of the lower lip.

There are small chips to the stone surface particularly at the tip of the nose, chin and mouth, and the outer edges of the ears. There is a slightly larger chip behind the ear on the left side.

description.value: Statuette of a king:  the figure of a beardless king wearing a white crown, the weight of which seems to be pushing out the tops of his huge ears. Wrapped in a short, stiff robe, he strides forward on his left leg. Perhaps the most striking aspect of the figure is the sense of age conveyed by the stoop of the king's shoulders, the forward thrust of his neck, and the droop (possibly somewhat exaggerated by weathering) of his long, pointed chin. Though a few would disagree, most believe that this is a depiction of an aged king. The robe is the type worn by kings during the sed-festival. This ceremony of royal rejuvenation was already in existence at the beginning of the First Dynasty. Here, the garment has the form of robes shown on other Early Dynastic representations of this ceremony. Unlike other versions of the robe, however, the material is patterned, with a design of diamond shapes bordered by two bands of guilloche. The designs were carved with such plasticity that even the under-and-over intertwining of the strips in the guilloche bands can still be seen. The effect strongly suggests woven designs in a heavy fabric, rather than painting on leather, as has sometimes been suggested. The most singular feature of the robe is a sort of flap that hangs down over each shoulder. These "epaulets" are worn and cracked and extremely hard to see, but the better-preserved example, on the left shoulder, apparently has a  scalloped edge. The objects appear to be unique, and no one has yet come up with a satisfactory identification or explanation, apart from a tentative (and unlikely) suggestion that they might represent animal paws. The arms of the figure are held at the front, by the fold of the cloak, and it is possible that the band of the robe hung over the right hand.

description.value: Part of a fine, almost white, limestone figure of a woman.  Upper half of woman standing with her left arm at the side, and the right arm bent up holding a lotus flower between her breasts. Around her neck is a necklace of biconical beads with a central pendant. Her hair is shown in a typical Egyptian fashion, rather static, it might be covered with a veil and even a high diadem has been suggested. Her face is oval with a pointed chin, large eyes, slightly sloping downwards, which are only slightly worked, and a small mouth with a slight indicated smile. The breasts are conical, the shoulders sloping; the arms are not separated from the body, their upper parts sturdy and thinning towards the forearms.  The statuette is not entirely finished though it is used like a finished object; diadem, eyes and ears, which are of enormous size, are incomplete and chisel marks remain all over the surface. The back is flat. Traces of gilding remain on the necklace and of a painted band at the waist.

description.value: Terracotta figure of a Roman soldier subduing an armed warrior.  A group, probably of Hadrian, in military dress but bare-headed, menacing with a sword a kneeling captive whom he grasps by the hair. The emperor wears a cuirass with shoulder-pieces and pteryges over a short tunic; a cingulum is knotted round his waist. He has arm-protectors and greaves and wears a bulla hanging round his neck. A diadem is worn, the tie of which hangs onto his right shoulder; an eagle or other raptor perches on his left shoulder. The captive is half-kneeling with his body and head to the front, and holds a sword and an oval shield. He wears a full beard, and long locks fall from his hair on both sides of his face. The group is set on a plain-faced plinth. The back is plain, with a ragged vent pierced through a circular depression produced in the mould. Hollow; two-piece mould. Micaceous orange-brown Nile silt with a red-brown surface; traces of a white dressing on the front.

description.value: Nude figure of the Seal Bearer Tjetji: Tjetji is shown in the classic pose of a standing official, with his left leg advanced, a long staff in his left hand, and a sekhem scepter (now lost) held horizontally in his right hand. The arms of this statue were made separately and pegged to the body, and the feet tenoned into a separate base. He has a long, slender torso and limbs with little indication of musculature; a somewhat overlarge head and very large eyes; a face that tapers to a narrow jaw, with a broad mouth curved in a tense-looking smile, set off by folds descending from the nostrils. The staff and scepter were also separate pieces, inserted through the holes in Tjetji's hands. The figure was once fully painted according to the usual conventions, with the body dark red, the hair and nipples black, and the finger- and toenails white. The eyes are inlaid with white limestone and obsidian, set in copper frames. The top of the plinth is incised with hieroglyphic text.

description.value: Terracotta ithyphallic Harpocrates figure holding jar. A naked youth, modelled in the round and seated on a rectangular plinth with his legs extended in front of him, the knees raised. The head is turned to his left and is shaved. A gigantic phallus projects from between his legs, sloping slightly downwards; its end is lost. On the phallus, held by both hands near its base, rests an Egyptian style amphora with handles placed midway on its body and an upright double beaded rim.      Solid, made in a two-piece mould. There are possible traces of an overall white coating that was painted red. Micaceous red-brown Nile silt with a thick dark-grey core and abundant gold mica, organics, quartz and white inclusions.

description.value: Terracotta reclining Ithyphallic figure plaque, possibly Priapus. A reclining naked man with  receding hair and a beard, his legs extending to his right, the left bent and close to the ground, the right with the knee raised. He leans his left elbow and  forearm on a pile of cushions, and his right arm and hand hold his large phallus upright against his right side and rising almost level with the top of his head. His left hand holds a small unrecognized object (a looped garland or a small pot?) against his corpulent belly. The figure is modelled in relief with a flat back and was probably made in a one piece mould; it has a low curving plinth, hollow underneath. White coating and painted red. Red-brown Nile silt. Feet missing.

description.value: Bronze figure of Isis seated and suckling Harpocrates: Isis, the archetypal mother goddess, is represented characteristically as a woman presenting her breast to suckle her son who sits on her lap. description.value: Terracotta figure of a boy holding a lyre. A standing adolescent youth, modelled in the round and holding a lyre. He stands four-square with his head slightly inclined to the left, wearing a large himation draped diagonally over his left shoulder leaving his right shoulder and chest bare; the himation is caught up by and covers his bent left arm and hand, an end hanging down; the other end is slung over his left shoulder and falls down his back. His feet, probably shod, show under the edge of the himation. In his lowered right hand he holds a lyre with a tortoiseshell sound-box. His hair has curls on each side of his face, is peaked at the top of the head and is brushed back to the rear. The figure has well-modelled detail on the back, and stands on a rectangular stepped plinth, which is hollow underneath. Hollow, from two-piece mould: it is possible, but by no means certain, that the head and the plinth were made separately and applied. Much of the overall white dressing remains. The flesh is painted pink and the hair dark red. Touches of rose madder can be seen on the edge of the himation that falls from his left hand. There is dark-red paint on the crossbar of the lyre and yellow on its sound-box; the top of the plinth is painted blue. Pale-buff clay with rare very fine gold mica  and sparse fine grey-black inclusions.

description.value: Head of terracotta figure.  A woman’s head broken from a figure; the hair has a central parting and is drawn back to a double bun. She wears an ivy-wreath, damaged as it passes over the top of the head; the hair is not detailed between the wreath and the bun. Two grooves cross her long neck and her chin is dimpled. She may wear crescentearrings, surviving only at the right ear, or it may be the lobe of the ear.  Mould-made, with hand-modelled detail: the wreath, the bun, the hair and the earring/ lobe. Micaceous brown Nile silt with a greybrown core; traces of a white dressing on the face, neck and the front of the hair and the wreath; pink paint on the bun.

description.value: Head of terracotta female figure.  A woman's head, broken from a figure; the hair is parted in the middle and waves back to be covered by her himation, drawn over her head: this shawl is not indicated over much of the head, but is shown at the back of the neck; the neckline of her chiton appears just above the break in front.  Mould-made separately from its body, and the part of the himation behind the neck was applied over the join: the break in the peg which was inserted into the body has been smoothed in modern times to allow the head to stand. Micaceous brown Nile silt with a dark-pink core and some inclusions, apparently sand.
